\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Uh . . . hello, Dr. Grant. Do you have a minute?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  As a matter of fact, I do. So what do you need, Ron?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Well, you wrote on my questionnaire "Come and see me."
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933 
 Ah, yes. Ron, there are a few problems with the way you set your questionnaire up. I'm sorry to say that I don't think you've thought out the statements very well. It was a prime example of why so many people complain about filling out questionnaires. Yo
u might even alienate your subjects with a questionnaire like this.
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Oh. I don't want . . . What did I do?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Don't look so discouraged. Several of your classmates have had similar problems. OK. So, what did you do? Well, for one
 thing, people get really annoyed with "and" statements.
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  "And" statements? Uh, what do you mean by "and" statements?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Well, let's say you get a questionnaire statement like "I like fruit and vegetables" with the choices of "y
es" or "no." Well, if you don't like fruit and vegetables, you check the "no" box and if you do, the "yes" box. No problem. But what do you check if you like fruit, but not vegetables?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Oh, I see.
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  You've several "and" statements in your questionnaire which need to be taken care of.
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  OK. Anything else?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Yes, there was}{\insrsid13533077 ,}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  actually. Can I see your questionnaire to jog my memory?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Sure. Here it is.
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Thanks. This statement. "
Males are better critical thinkers than females." I can tell you now what answers you'll get for that item. Most, if not all males will mark "yes" - and females will mark "no." It's kind of silly to have a statement that you already know how your subjects
 will answer. And it won't be of much use for collecting data, will it?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  No, I guess it won't.
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933 
 Furthermore, women who get this will be really annoyed with the implication that men think more effectively than they do. And, once you've angered your subjects, they won't be very cooperative in answering the rest of the questionnaire. They might sabota
ge your results by not being truthful or they'll become "critical thinkers" and write their criticism all over your questionnaire. But chances are they'll just dump the questionnaire in the trash.
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Yeah. I can see that. But, how can I phrase it?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933 
 Well, I'm not really sure what you're trying to find out here. Perhaps you want to know if people consider critical thinking to be more prevalent in a particular gender - in which case you could write: "The ability to think critically i
s gender-based." Is that the information you wanted?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Yeah. That's it. Anything else?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Look at this statement, "I'm unable to think critically." That's like saying "I'm stupid." How many people would answer "yes" to that? See?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933 
 What I'd like you to do is go through every statement on your questionnaire very critically. Think: what information do I want? How can I phrase my statement to get meaningful results? Maybe you and a classmate could discuss each other's questionnaires.

\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  That's a good idea.
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Woman Professor:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  Ron, I'd like to look it over once more before you pass it out. OK?
\par }{\insrsid4805435 
\par }{\b\insrsid4805435\charrsid4805435 Man Student:}{\insrsid9005868\charrsid15341933  OK, Dr. Grant. Thank you for your help.
\par }{\insrsid15341933 
